// texts.en.js — Numerological texts (English)
// Translated from texts.pt.js — PT-BR → EN-US
// Author citations use original English sources where identifiable
// (Balliett, Campbell, Sepharial, Kozminsky all wrote in English)

/* ════════════════════════════════════════════════
   TEXTS DATABASE
════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
var TEXTS_EN = {};

TEXTS_EN[1] = {
  title: 'The Pioneer',
  essence: 'The One is the point of origin, the primordial impulse that precedes all form. For Pythagoras, the Monad was the principle from which all other numbers emerge — the father of them all, anterior to every other. The 1 vibrates with the energy of pure creation: it exists before the void, and for that reason inhabits it without anxiety. It is the consciousness that recognizes itself for the first time and decides to act. L. Dow Balliett described the 1 as the force that passes through all obstacles — only directable, never stoppable. It requires no approval, because approval presupposes an external judgment, and the 1 acknowledges only its own inner law.',
  motivation: 'With 1 as your Soul Urge, you are driven by a profound desire for autonomy and originality. At your deepest level, what your soul most wants is to be inaugural — to create something that was absent from the world before you arrived. There is an inner hunger for independence that, when suppressed, transforms into quiet frustration or an irritability difficult to name. Your inner world is that of an explorer: you feel before you understand, and act before you plan.',
  impression: 'Those around you perceive you as decisive, confident, and commanding in presence. You enter a room and something shifts — people notice. This impression of natural leadership can be a gift or a weight: some feel drawn and reassured by it, while others withdraw for no apparent reason. You rarely seem hesitant in others\' eyes, even when you are inwardly still deliberating — which sometimes prevents people from drawing near to offer help.',
  expression: 'Your path of expression is one of creation and leadership. You have the gift of initiation — of projects, movements, relationships, ideas. The talent lies in the beginning; sustaining is the lesson. Your natural gift is seeing possibilities where others see obstacles, and articulating a vision in ways that inspire action. Florence Campbell observes that the expressive 1 carries in its name the seed of something the world was still waiting to know.',
  lifepath: 'Your mission in this life is to learn to be yourself, completely. That sounds simple — and it is profound. The challenge of 1 as a Life Path is to resist the pressures of conformity without becoming inflexible; to lead without dominating; to be original without being solitary. You came to demonstrate that there is a different way of doing things — and you will only demonstrate it after first believing it yourself. Your journey is frequently marked by fresh starts, each one more authentic than the last.',
  shadow: 'The 1 in imbalance turns all attention inward, becoming incapable of receiving. The need to be first can transform into destructive competitiveness. Healthy independence closes itself into isolation. The challenge is to learn that accepting help is an act of courage — and that true leadership elevates others rather than diminishing them.',
  day: 'Born on a day of vibration 1, you brought with you the gift of instinctive initiative — the capacity to take the first step before others have perceived that a step was necessary. This talent was not earned; it arrived with you. Balliett described this gift as the spark that exists before the fire: not learned courage, but a natural orientation toward the beginning of all things. Your innate instrument is clarity of direction — you know, without needing to calculate, that there is a path to open.',
  attitude: 'Your first response to the world is one of assertion. Before processing, before calculating, you have already responded — with posture, with position, with presence. Kozminsky would call this the reflex of the pioneer: your nervous system was calibrated for the vanguard. In situations of tension, you assume control before you realize you have done so. The challenge is that this swiftness may appear inconsiderate to others, when it is simply your particular way of being alive before conscious thought. The instinctive reaction precedes intention.',
  power: 'The Power Number 1 reveals itself after maturity as a leadership that no longer needs to prove itself. What in youth was assertion becomes in time a serene sense of direction; what was a need to be first transforms into the capacity to open paths for those who come after. Campbell observes that the mature 1 leads by quiet example. Your synthesis is the independence that includes — the strength that inspires rather than dominates. Here, the pioneer has ripened and what remains is mastery without need of demonstration.'
};

TEXTS_EN[2] = {
  title: 'The Diplomat',
  essence: 'The Dyad, for the Pythagoreans, was the birth of duality: the moment in which the One divides and recognizes itself in relation to the Other. The 2 is the number of relational consciousness — it exists in relation to a second presence, and finds in that interdependence its greatest strength. Sepharial describes the 2 as the vibration of perfect receptivity — that which listens before speaking and feels before understanding. There is a rare intelligence in this. The 2 perceives what lies between the lines, in the silences, in the withheld gestures. Where the 1 divides, the 2 connects.',
  motivation: 'Your soul is moved by the need for harmony and belonging. What you most deeply desire is genuine connection — to be truly understood and to truly understand another. There is in you a sensitivity almost painful in its acuity to relational dissonance: a misplaced word, an off-key tone of voice, and you feel it before you process it. This emotional radar is an extraordinary gift that you often treat as a burden — when it is, in fact, your native language.',
  impression: 'People perceive you as gentle, welcoming, and trustworthy. You have a natural talent for making people feel seen and heard — and this creates a quiet magnetism around you. The impression you project is of someone patient, diplomatic, who never pushes. The challenge is that some may interpret this softness as indecision or lack of personal opinion — which rarely corresponds to the inner truth.',
  expression: 'Your expressive gift is mediation and creative cooperation. You are the catalyst that makes collaborators more than the sum of their parts. Your intelligence operates in the field of nuance: you perceive what each person needs, what each situation demands, and you have the ability to translate this into concrete action. Kozminsky observes that the expressive 2 rarely appears as the hero of the story — but without this number, the story loses its coherence.',
  lifepath: 'Your mission is to learn to integrate without losing yourself. Life will place before you situations that require you to choose between the peace of the group and your own truth — and it is precisely there that your growth occurs. The 2 on the Life Path frequently passes through relationships that function as mirrors: the other shows you what is still in the process of being discovered within yourself. Your journey is one of loving individuation.',
  shadow: 'The 2 in imbalance becomes dependent, submissive, and indirectly expressive. The need for approval can lead you to suppress your own voice to the point of losing sight of it. The accumulated resentment — of all the times you yielded against your will — can transform into reactive passivity. The central challenge is to learn that true harmony includes and honors your own truth.',
  day: 'Born on a day of vibration 2, you arrived equipped with a relational sensitivity that functions as an instrument of precision — you perceive what lies between the lines of any human situation before anyone has articulated it in words. Sepharial described this gift as the intelligence that inhabits the space between beings. It is not a learned gift: from early on, you detected invisible dissonances, and you felt the emotional state of a room before entering it. This radar is your most genuine talent — even when you experience it as a burden.',
  attitude: 'Instinctively, your first response to any tension is to seek the middle ground. Before evaluating whether conflict is necessary or healthy, you are already mediating — softening, checking that everyone is well, tending to the tone. This is the automatic reaction of the 2: to harmonize before analyzing. Kozminsky would call this the instinct of the cooperative mirror. The risk is that this reflex may silence your own voice in situations where speaking would be precisely what true harmony requires. Instinctive pacification is gift and trap in equal measure.',
  power: 'The Power Number 2 emerges in maturity as diplomacy with roots. What once manifested as a need for approval transforms, over the years, into genuine relational wisdom — the capacity to build bridges between people and perspectives without erasing oneself in the process. Campbell observes that the mature 2 has discovered that its strength was always listening — but now listens without dissolving. Your synthesis is the cooperation that preserves the self: the art of being completely present for the other without abdicating yourself.'
};

TEXTS_EN[3] = {
  title: 'The Creator',
  essence: 'The Triad was, for Pythagoras, the first complete number: it has beginning, middle, and end. The 3 is the synthesis of the 1 and the 2 — of individual impulse and relational consciousness — resulting in something entirely new: creative expression. It is the number of manifestation, communication, and joy. Balliett wrote that where the 3 vibrates, the world is illuminated — because it asks its questions with beauty, even when the answers are still under construction. The 3 is the artist, the communicator, the storyteller of numerology.',
  motivation: 'Your soul desires to express itself — in any form, through any medium. Word, body, music, hands, laughter: there is in you a visceral need to externalize what lies within. To suppress this need creates a particular sadness — diffuse, without easy name. You were made to create, and when the creative cycle is interrupted, something essential in you waits for a channel of return.',
  impression: 'People perceive you as charismatic, animated, and full of ideas. You have the gift of making any conversation more interesting, any environment more alive. There is a lightness in you that people find reassuring. The risk is that this vibrant presence may be read as superficiality — when in truth what happens is that you process life through expression, and silence is merely a pause between creations.',
  expression: 'You have the gift of communicating in ways that touch people. Your most powerful tool is language — spoken or in any form of translation from the inner to the outer. Campbell describes the expressive 3 as the one who carries in the name the promise that beauty has a purpose. Your greatest realization will come when you stop treating your creativity as entertainment and begin treating it as vocation.',
  lifepath: 'Your mission is to bring joy and meaning through expression. Life will ask you to find your true voice — the one that vibrates when you are completely present. The 3 on the Life Path frequently passes through periods of forced silence — the loss of employment, of a relationship, even of literal voice — which are, paradoxically, invitations to the deepening of authentic expression.',
  shadow: 'The 3 in imbalance scatters its energy in a thousand directions without completing any. Creativity without discipline becomes chaos; the gift of communication becomes dispersal; the pursuit of joy becomes an escape from depth. The challenge is to learn that the most powerful expression is born from the quiet center, and that the completed work holds more power than ten abandoned ideas.',
  day: 'Born on a day of vibration 3, you brought the gift of expression as your native language. Communication — in whatever form it takes — is not something you learned; it is the mode through which you exist in the world. Balliett observed that the 3 carries joy as a tool of creation, not as an ornament. Your expressiveness is the innate instrument: the capacity to transform experience into communication that illuminates what was obscure to others. Before any technique, before any schooling, this gift was already operating fully within you.',
  attitude: 'Your first impulse before the world is to make it more interesting. Instinctively, before deeply assessing a situation, you have already illuminated the room with an observation, an image, an added note of color. This is the reflex of the 3: to bring lightness to what has not yet taken form. Kozminsky would describe this reaction as instinctive illumination — the gift of making space breathe. The challenge is that this tendency to lighten the weight may be perceived as superficiality when it is, in fact, an emotional intelligence that operates through the beautiful and the light.',
  power: 'The Power Number 3 consolidates in maturity as a creative voice that no longer requires approval to exist. What was once expression in order to be seen transforms into expression in order to be real; the creativity that sought recognition matures into art that serves. Campbell wrote that the mature 3 finally finds the difference between what it creates for the world and what it creates for the soul — and discovers they are the same thing. Your synthesis is communication with depth: lightness earned from within, not from the surface.'
};

TEXTS_EN[4] = {
  title: 'The Builder',
  essence: 'The Tetrad was sacred to the Pythagoreans: the square, the four directions, the four seasons, the four elements. The 4 is the number of concrete manifestation — the idea that meets the earth and takes root. It is the architect, the craftsman, the manager, the farmer. Sepharial describes it as the vibration of tangible reality — the one that trusts in work because it knows that work makes things happen. There is an honesty in the 4 that can appear blunt, but is simply the language of solidity.',
  motivation: 'Your soul is driven by the need for stability and concrete construction. What you most want, at your core, is to see the result of your work — something that lasts, that is solid, that can be touched. There is a deep pleasure in the process itself: planning, executing, adjusting, completing. When this cycle is interrupted by external instability or inconsistency in others, you feel a disturbance that goes beyond logic.',
  impression: 'People perceive you as reliable, responsible, and realistic. You are the one who shows up, who keeps promises, who gets straight to the point. This impression of solidity attracts people who need an anchor — which can burden you with responsibilities that arrived uninvited. You may also be perceived as rigid by those who operate on intuition and improvisation, who secretly admire your consistency.',
  expression: 'Your gift is transforming visions into reality. You are the link between the abstract and the concrete — the person who takes someone\'s brilliant idea and makes it function in the real world. Campbell observes that the expressive 4 is the foundation upon which the dreams of others are built — and that is an essential role, never a secondary one. Your greatest realization will come through consistent work, and every brick laid with care counts.',
  lifepath: 'Your mission is to build something that lasts — a family, a company, a system, a body of work. Life will ask you to learn to work with limits rather than against them; to find freedom within structure. The 4 on the Life Path frequently passes through situations that test patience and the capacity to sustain effort without immediate gratification — and it is precisely there that character is forged.',
  shadow: 'The 4 in imbalance becomes rigid, controlling, and trapped in routine. The valorization of hard work can turn into workaholism; the sense of responsibility can become an inability to delegate; realism can harden into chronic pessimism. The challenge is to learn that structure exists to serve life — and that flexibility is part of mature solidity.',
  day: 'Born on a day of vibration 4, you brought structure as an innate gift. From the beginning, you perceived what needed organizing before any instruction — the talent for identifying what works, what is out of place, what needs a foundation before it can advance. Sepharial described the 4 as the hand that finds the right angle where others see only chaos. This gift of construction was not learned; it arrived with you as a natural mode of perceiving the world — the eye that detects structure before the complete form is visible.',
  attitude: 'Before any new situation, your instinctive reaction is to assess what is concrete and what is viable. Before growing enthusiastic, you have already checked the foundation. Before agreeing, you have already identified what has not yet been thought through. This pragmatic reflex is the signature of the 4 in response mode: the instinct to test solidity before trusting the shine. Kozminsky would call this testing the weight before taking the step. The challenge is that this instinctive caution may sound like skepticism to those who operate on vision — when it is simply your form of love for what is real.',
  power: 'The Power Number 4 reveals itself in maturity as constructive mastery — the capacity to raise things that last. What in youth was work by necessity transforms into work as legacy; the discipline that was obligation becomes artisanal wisdom. Campbell observes that the mature 4 builds now with pleasure what it once built with effort. Your synthesis is competence with soul: the craftsman who knows precisely why every piece matters. Solidity is no longer restriction — it is the foundation upon which freedom can, at last, exist.'
};

TEXTS_EN[5] = {
  title: 'The Adventurer',
  essence: 'The 5 stands at the center of the sequence from 1 to 9 — and this is significant. It is the number of perpetual motion, freedom, and adaptation. Kozminsky describes it as the vibration of the complete human being: two arms, two legs, and a head — the number that most resembles life in motion. The 5 is curious by nature; stagnation is physically painful to it. It learns through direct experience, and carries within itself an archive of lives lived intensely.',
  motivation: 'Your soul is driven by freedom and experience. What you most want is to be able to go — to new territories of experience, of thought, of sensation. There is in you a radical openness to the unknown that may be unsettling to those who love you, but that is simply your way of being alive. When confined — by routines, by suffocating relationships, by monotonous work — you begin to wither from the inside out, and your spirit calls for movement.',
  impression: 'People perceive you as versatile, fascinating, and unpredictable. You carry an energy that makes any situation more interesting — there is always the feeling that something might happen when you are near. This impression of dynamism attracts people, but can also generate distrust: the 5 seems difficult to hold, and some interpret this as a lack of commitment — when in reality it is simply a different form of loyalty.',
  expression: 'Your gift is creative adaptation. You have a rare capacity to function in different environments, to communicate with people of varying backgrounds, to find solutions where others see insurmountable obstacles. Balliett observes that the expressive 5 is the universal translator — the one who understands the language of every world it visits. Your greatest realization will come when you use your versatility in service of something larger than immediate pleasure.',
  lifepath: 'Your mission is to explore the breadth of human experience and bring back wisdom to share. Life will ask you to learn the difference between freedom and escape; between adventure and irresponsibility; between openness and the inability to deepen. The 5 on the Life Path frequently passes through radical changes that, only in retrospect, reveal themselves as necessary redirections.',
  shadow: 'The 5 in imbalance becomes impulsive, scattered, and dependent on external stimulation. The pursuit of freedom can turn into escape from all responsibility; openness to new experiences can become the inability to deepen any one of them. The challenge is to learn that the deepest freedom is internal — and remains intact regardless of geographic coordinates.',
  day: 'Born on a day of vibration 5, you brought adaptability as your natural instrument — an openness to the unexpected that functions not as tolerance of the unpredictable, but as genuine appetite for it. Kozminsky described the 5 as the one born knowing that the world has more doors than any map could show. Your gift of adaptation is innate: you did not need to learn to improvise — improvisation is your native tongue. Before any method, before any training, you already knew how to navigate the unplanned.',
  attitude: 'Your first reaction to any new situation is to open options. Instinctively, before committing to one path, you have already identified three others. Before closing, you have already questioned whether closing is truly necessary. This is the reflex of the 5: the automatic exploration of the space of possibilities. Balliett would call this the instinct of freedom that precedes decision. The challenge is that this reflex can create hesitation where the situation calls for rapid commitment — and may be perceived as lack of conviction when it is adaptive intelligence operating in real time.',
  power: 'The Power Number 5 matures as the wisdom of lived experience. What in youth was the pursuit of stimulation transforms, with time, into a generosity of knowledge — the capacity to share what was learned across many different worlds. Campbell observes that the mature 5 no longer runs toward the next experience: it already knows that the next territory lies within. Your synthesis is freedom with roots: versatility that now serves rather than merely explores. The adventurer has become a guide — and the entire journey has found a new purpose.'
};

TEXTS_EN[6] = {
  title: 'The Guardian',
  essence: 'The 6 was called by the Pythagoreans the "perfect number" — because it equals the sum of its divisors (1+2+3=6). This mathematical perfection reflects its essence: harmony, balance, care. The 6 is the number of home, family, loving responsibility, and beauty as service. Balliett described it as the vibration that sustains the world while others explore it — and there is a quiet nobility in this function that the 6 rarely recognizes in itself.',
  motivation: 'Your soul is driven by love and the need to care. What you most deeply desire is to create a world in which the people around you feel safe, loved, and whole. There is in you an aesthetic sensitivity — you suffer in the presence of the ugly, the discordant, the neglected — that people sometimes misread, but which is in truth a form of emotional and sensory intelligence of the highest order.',
  impression: 'People perceive you as warm, responsible, and aesthetically refined. You have a presence that conveys safety — people feel at ease in your space, in the broadest sense of the word. This impression of reliability causes many to bring you their problems, their burdens, their responsibilities — which can be beautiful when reciprocal, and exhausting when one-sided.',
  expression: 'Your gift is transformative care. You have the capacity to create environments — physical, relational, emotional — that nourish the growth of others. Campbell observes that the expressive 6 carries in its name the capacity to heal by the simple act of being present. Your greatest realization will come through some form of service that integrates your aesthetic sensitivity and your capacity to nurture.',
  lifepath: 'Your mission is to learn to love with limits. Life will place before you situations that require you to choose between your own well-being and the well-being of others — and it is precisely in that tension that your growth occurs. The 6 on the Life Path frequently carries heavy family or community responsibilities, and the central lesson is to discover that caring for yourself is a prerequisite for caring for another.',
  shadow: 'The 6 in imbalance becomes controlling beneath the mask of care, martyred, and incapable of allowing others to make their own mistakes. The need for harmony can become the suppression of healthy conflict; love can become suffocation; responsibility can become chronic guilt. The challenge is to learn the difference between caring and controlling — and that mature love respects the autonomy of others.',
  day: 'Born on a day of vibration 6, you brought care as your native language — a sensitivity to the environment and to people that operates independently of any conscious effort. From the beginning, you perceived what needed attention before anyone asked. Balliett described the 6 as the one born knowing that beauty and care are the same word. Your innate gift is the capacity to create harmony — not through technique, but through temperament. This talent for nurturing arrived with you, before any formal learning about service or love.',
  attitude: 'Instinctively, your first reaction to any imbalance is to try to correct it. Before evaluating whether it is your role to do so, you are already organizing, caring, attempting to restore the harmony that was disturbed. This is the automatic reflex of the 6: the impulse to care before thinking. Kozminsky would describe it as the instinct of restoration — the hand that reaches out before the glass has finished falling. The challenge is that this instinctive generosity can become a weight when operated without discernment — when care is offered where it was not requested and where it will find no reciprocity.',
  power: 'The Power Number 6 manifests in maturity as love that knows its own limits. What was once unrestricted care transforms into service with wisdom; the need to harmonize converts into the capacity to create lasting beauty. Campbell wrote that the mature 6 has discovered that loving well is different from loving much. Your synthesis is care with discernment: the capacity to offer what truly nourishes, rather than what merely reassures. The guardian has become wise — and love, from an automatic reflex, has become a deliberate art.'
};

TEXTS_EN[7] = {
  title: 'The Seeker',
  essence: 'The 7 is the most sacred number across virtually all esoteric traditions. Seven musical notes, seven colors of the rainbow, seven days of the week, seven chakras. For the Pythagoreans, the 7 was the number that exists beyond generation and dissolution within the Decade — a quality of mystical self-sufficiency. It is the number of deep knowledge, analysis, and inner silence. Kozminsky describes it as the vibration that hears what no one else hears and sees what lies beyond the veil.',
  motivation: 'Your soul is driven by the pursuit of true knowledge — beyond information, beyond data, toward deep understanding. What you most want, at your core, is to understand: how things work, why they exist, what lies beneath the surface. There is in you an extraordinarily rich inner life that few people come to know, because words rarely seem sufficient to describe it.',
  impression: 'People perceive you as intelligent, reserved, and somehow mysterious. You have a quality of observation that makes people feel they have been seen with greater depth than they were prepared for. This contemplative presence can intimidate or fascinate. You rarely seem completely available — there is always a part of you that remains in contemplation, and this creates a magnetism you probably underestimate.',
  expression: 'Your gift is the analysis and synthesis of knowledge. You have a rare capacity to go to the core of questions, to find the underlying pattern, to name what everyone felt but no one had articulated. Sepharial observes that the expressive 7 transforms experience into wisdom — by the quality of attention, never by the quantity. Your greatest realization will come when you learn to share what you know, even before you are certain you have understood everything.',
  lifepath: 'Your mission is to seek the truth and make it accessible. Life will ask you to learn to balance the need for withdrawal with the need for connection; analysis with faith; skepticism with openness. The 7 on the Life Path frequently passes through crises of meaning that are, in truth, invitations to spiritual deepening — and each one delivers a denser layer of wisdom.',
  shadow: 'The 7 in imbalance isolates itself, becomes cynical, and uses intelligence as a tool of emotional distancing. The pursuit of knowledge can turn into infinite postponement; the need for certainty can become paralysis; depth can become intellectual arrogance. The challenge is to learn that complete wisdom includes the heart — and that vulnerability is one of the most advanced forms of intelligence.',
  day: 'Born on a day of vibration 7, you arrived equipped with a gaze that naturally deepens. Analysis, observation, the search for what lies beneath the surface are not habits you cultivated — they are your natural way of inhabiting the world. Sepharial described the gift of the 7 as the vision that goes beyond the veil without requiring permission. Your innate instrument is penetrating attention: you notice what others pass over, and you have carried this gift from before you had words to name it. The depth arrived with you.',
  attitude: 'Before any new situation, your instinctive reflex is to observe before participating. You analyze the space, assess the dynamics, identify what has gone unsaid — and only then consider your entry. This is the instinct of the 7: the contemplative distance that precedes any action. Kozminsky would call this the step back that makes the whole picture visible. The challenge is that this stance of observation may be perceived as coldness or disinterest, when in truth it is the way in which you honor what you encounter — and the only environment in which your intelligence can operate at full capacity.',
  power: 'The Power Number 7 emerges in maturity as wisdom that can be shared. What was once knowledge accumulated in silence transforms, with time, into the capacity to guide — to render accessible what was won in the depths. Campbell observes that the mature 7 has ceased to guard knowledge as personal treasure and learned to use it as a lantern. Your synthesis is intelligence with heart: the analysis that now includes compassion. The solitary seeker has matured into a teacher — and the silence that once isolated now creates space for others to grow.'
};

TEXTS_EN[8] = {
  title: 'The Achiever',
  essence: 'The 8 is the only number that, rotated 90°, becomes the infinite (∞). This image reveals its nature: it is the number of power that circulates, regenerates, and persists. For the Pythagoreans, it represented justice — the cosmic law of balance: what rises falls, what is given returns. Balliett called it the vibration of conscious abundance — the wealth that comes from mastery of oneself, and that for this reason endures.',
  motivation: 'Your soul is driven by the desire for power and conscious material achievement. What you most want, at your core, is impact — to see that your actions have changed something in the tangible world, that you have left a real mark. There is in you an ambition that transcends vanity: a visceral understanding that resources and influence are tools of change. When this impulse is repressed by limiting beliefs about money or power, a tension is created that manifests in everything.',
  impression: 'People perceive you as powerful, authoritative, and competent. You enter a room and the dynamics shift — hierarchies become more conscious. This presence of authority can inspire respect or generate resistance, depending on how it is exercised. You are rarely ignored — and rarely need to ask for attention; it arrives naturally.',
  expression: 'Your gift is executive leadership and the capacity to materialize on a large scale. You have an intelligence for systems, for power, and for resources that, when aligned with purpose, can move mountains. Campbell observes that the expressive 8 carries in its name the capacity to build empires — the question is always: in service of what. Your greatest realization will come when you integrate power and purpose as inseparable.',
  lifepath: 'Your mission is to learn to work with the material forces of the world without being consumed by them. Life will ask you to confront questions of power, money, and authority repeatedly — as schooling, never as punishment. The 8 on the Life Path frequently alternates between periods of great abundance and radical loss, and the lesson is the same in both: equanimity as foundation.',
  shadow: 'The 8 in imbalance becomes controlling, materialistic, and obsessed with status. The fear of vulnerability can become emotional armor; ambition can become instrumental cruelty; the pursuit of power can destroy the relationships that matter most. The challenge is to learn that true power does not require domination to affirm itself — and that generosity is the most sophisticated expression of strength.',
  day: 'Born on a day of vibration 8, you brought authority as a natural presence — an innate capacity to assess structures of power and resources that was not learned, but arrived as a built-in instrument. Balliett described the gift of the 8 as the sense of what has weight and what does not — the intelligence of consequence. From early on, you instinctively knew who decides, what is of value, and what requires force to exist. This executive talent is your innate gift: the capacity to see the world in terms of what sustains and what collapses.',
  attitude: 'Your first reaction to any environment is an automatic assessment of power and structure. Before any conscious analysis, you have already identified who holds authority, what resources are available, and what needs to be organized. This is the reflex of the 8: the executive reading that precedes deliberate thought. Kozminsky would call this the instinct of the systems architect. The challenge is that this instinctive assertiveness may be perceived as relational coldness — when it is simply your intelligence doing what it has always done: mapping what is real before deciding how to act.',
  power: 'The Power Number 8 consolidates in maturity as leadership with integrated purpose. What in youth was ambition of conquest transforms, with time, into the capacity to use power in service of something that outlasts oneself. Campbell writes that the mature 8 has discovered that the most enduring wealth is built when power serves rather than is exercised for its own sake. Your synthesis is authority with ethics: the achiever who has learned that true legacy is measured by the impact that persists after titles and positions have been forgotten.'
};

TEXTS_EN[9] = {
  title: 'The Humanitarian',
  essence: 'The 9 is the last of the simple numbers — and the most inclusive of all, because it contains every other within itself. Mathematically, any number added to the 9 and reduced returns to itself: 9+3=12→3, 9+7=16→7. This unique property led the Pythagoreans to call the 9 "the horizon" — the boundary that encompasses everything. It is the number of universal compassion, completion, and wisdom won through experience. Kozminsky describes it as the vibration of the being who has walked all paths and for that reason understands each one.',
  motivation: 'Your soul is moved by compassion and the desire to contribute to something greater than yourself. What you most want, at your core, is for the world to be better for your having passed through it. There is in you a sensitivity to the pain of others that can be overwhelming — you feel collective suffering in a way that others are still developing the capacity for. This openness to the world is simultaneously your most precious gift and your deepest vulnerability.',
  impression: 'People perceive you as wise, generous, and broad of vision. You have a quality of presence that makes people feel received without judgment — and that is rare enough to be extraordinary. This impression of wisdom and welcome attracts people in search of guidance, which can be beautiful and exhausting in equal measure.',
  expression: 'Your gift is systemic vision and the capacity to serve in ways that transcend the personal. You have the ability to see patterns at human scale — what connects, what divides, what heals. Balliett observes that the expressive 9 carries in its name the capacity to complete cycles — personal, familial, collective. Your greatest realization will come through some form of service that integrates your worldview with your practical compassion.',
  lifepath: 'Your mission is to learn to love humanity without losing yourself in it. Life will ask you to practice active detachment: to give without expecting return, to help without needing recognition, to conclude without lamenting what was left behind. The 9 on the Life Path frequently passes through significant losses that, paradoxically, open space for something far greater than what was left.',
  shadow: 'The 9 in imbalance scatters its altruism, accumulates resentment over lack of reciprocity, and finds difficulty establishing limits without guilt. Compassion can become emotional codependence; broad vision can become inability to act in the immediate concrete; generosity can become systematic self-neglect. The challenge is to learn that you too are part of the humanity you wish to serve — and you deserve the same care you offer.',
  day: 'Born on a day of vibration 9, you arrived equipped with a natural openness to others — an empathy that did not need to be taught because it arrived as part of your structure of perception. Kozminsky described the gift of the 9 as the vision born already panoramic — the one that includes before it excludes. From early on, you felt the suffering of others before understanding it; you recognized humanity in others before you had words for it. Your innate instrument is compassion as a mode of being — an openness to the world that precedes any conscious decision to be open.',
  attitude: 'Instinctively, your first reaction to any situation is to widen the angle — to include what has been left out, to think of the people not present in the conversation, to consider consequences beyond the immediate. This is the reflex of the 9: the systemic vision that precedes individual judgment. Balliett would call this the instinct of the horizon — the tendency to see beyond the boundaries of what is asked. The challenge is that this instinctive openness can become indecision when the vision that includes everything finds difficulty choosing one single concrete direction in which to act.',
  power: 'The Power Number 9 matures as humanitarian wisdom with roots. What in youth was compassion that scattered in all directions transforms, with time, into service that knows where to apply itself. Campbell observes that the mature 9 no longer attempts to reach the entire world: it chooses where its presence makes a real difference — and offers itself completely. Your synthesis is love as deliberate practice: the generosity that has learned its own contours. The humanitarian has matured into a sage — and compassion, from an unlimited instinct, has become a gift that truly transforms.'
};

